-- pg_turbovec v1.17.0 -- Phase F-2: persistent ColBERT token index.
--
-- This file is a *reference mirror*. The authoritative install
-- script is generated by `cargo pgrx schema`.
--
-- v1.17.0 makes ColBERT late interaction INDEX-NATIVE: a persistent
-- on-disk token index, replacing F-1's per-call backend-cache build.
--
--   CREATE INDEX ON docs USING turbovec (tokens vec_colbert_ops);
--     -- tokens is a turbovec.vector[] column (per-doc token arrays)
--
--   SELECT id, score FROM turbovec.colbert_search(
--     'docs'::regclass, 'id', 'tokens', :q_tokens, 10);
--     -- now reads stage-1 from the persistent index (no per-call build;
--     -- the F-1 ~28 MB/call leak is eliminated on this path)
--
-- New SQL object: the vec_colbert_ops operator class over
-- turbovec.vector[] (support function max_sim, NO order-by operator --
-- so the planner can never select it for ORDER BY; reads go through
-- turbovec.colbert_search). cargo pgrx schema emits the CREATE
-- OPERATOR CLASS into the authoritative 1.16.0--1.17.0 upgrade script;
-- this reference mirror does not duplicate it.
--
-- WIRE FORMAT: additive bump 4 -> 5, strictly per index kind.
--   * A single-vector index (vec_cosine_ops / vec_ip_ops / vec_l2_ops
--     / vec_l1_ops over a `vector` column) STILL emits wire version 4
--     with a zeroed `kind` byte (page offset 30, formerly reserved).
--     Its relfile is BYTE-IDENTICAL to v1.16.0 (verified by tests).
--   * Only an index built `USING turbovec (col vec_colbert_ops)` over
--     a `vector[]` column is v5 (kind = KIND_COLBERT) -- a new shape
--     (per-token slots, doc TID repeated in the ids chain), IVF
--     (cell-contiguous tokens), tombstone-on-VACUUM.
--
-- MIGRATION: NO REINDEX. A v4 single-vector index decodes under the
-- v5 binary as kind = KIND_SINGLE (the kind byte was a reserved zero
-- on v4), so is_legacy_v4() never trips. There is no in-place
-- migration of a v4 single-vector index into a v5 ColBERT index; a
-- ColBERT index is built fresh. `ALTER EXTENSION pg_turbovec UPDATE
-- TO '1.17.0';` registers the new opclass and is sufficient.
